<section id="introspection">
    <h2>Introspection</h2>
    <p>I wrote a ton about what I feel at the moment after I finished watching the series, but I don't really mention how good the music is! From the OP <i>The Other Side of the Wall</i>, to the ED <i>A Page of My Story</i>, the Crown Handler's OP <i>LIES & TIES</i> and their ED <i>Nowhere Land</i>, and their original soundtrack... it's <i>really</i> good, or rather, it hits right for me and really immerse me in the setting completely. The smooth jazz sound accompanying both the action scenes (my favorite of the soundtrack would be ) and the espionage scenes (<i>Espionage Trap</i>) is exhilirating, entrancing at times. It got my blood pumping in excitement. Yuki Kajiura, the composer who also worked on Sword Art Online and Demon Slayer, really knocks it out of the park.</p>

    <p>Each character from Team White Pigeon appeals to me, from Dorothy and her adult appeal, Beatrice and her devotion to Charlotte and her ingenious mind, Chise and her Samurai bruiser way of thinking, Charlotte and her gap moe between heartful innocence and ambition to break down the wall and being a Queen.</p>

    <p>And the complicated Ange, who seems like a chuuni who keep mentioning Black Lizard Planet at first, but behind her quirkiness lies a competent former princess who has survived for years in espionage, and her quirkiness was sometimes a calculated move. Like how she pre-planned getting a life insurance on the guy that was about to betray her, just so she can pay for the guy's sister's operation. That moment stuck with me for a long time.</p>

    <p>The way the anime has anachronistic order is also very interesting. It's a very clever way to not introduce flashback as a method to explore the dynamic between the team, but it does mean you have to pay attention to the sequence of events, or you'll be confused on things (I'm still unsure if the movie takes place right after the anime series...)</p>

    <p>There's also OVAs that I didn't put in here, where we get to see the more CGDCT portion of the series. BUSY EASY MONEY is talking about what each character would do if they receive money (and the wholesome ending about them giving back to the laundry place... man, I missed them as a laundry place owner). Revealing Reviews talking about opera shows that Chise and Beatrice watch, with the story eerily similar to the dynamic between Beatrice, Ange, and Charlotte. I kinda have to grimace a bit as Beatrice doesn't know about the truth yet... and wonders if the movies would explore that at some point. Cost for Custom Cars talks about custom car design that each character likes, as each design really delve deep into what kind of character they are... especially Dorothy wanting to have a pocket designed to hold on alcohol.</p>

    <p>In a CAR, DOROTHY? Good god, you're such a girlfailure...</p>

    <p>Either way, I'll be eagerly awaiting for the last three movies to come out, and I'm willing to give this series a 9/10 rating, for both the series and the currently released movie trilogy.</p>
